@node "Installation" "Installation"
@prev "Main"
NOTE: At least Workbench 2.04 is needed to run show!!!

Show comes complete with an Installer script. Just double-click onĀtheĀ
"Show_Install" icon and proceed. There are three versions of show -
Show_020ffp and Showprefs_020ffp can be used if your Amiga has a >= 68020 processor
with a FPU. Show_020 and Showprefs_020 can be used if your Amiga have a  >= 68020
processor. Show and showprefs can be used with any combination of processor
and FPU.

The script installs two programs - the showĀpreferences program and the show
program itself. The installation procedure can sense that aĀprevious version
of Show was installed and asks if you want toĀoverwriteĀit.

You have the option to install the sample prefs file that came with this
archive. I would suggest that you install the sample preferences then edit
the entries later using the @{"preferencesĀprogram" link "showprefs" 0}.
@endnode

@node "whatis" "What is Show?"
@next "useshow"
@prev "Installation"
Just what exactly is Show? Show is a program that associates suffixesĀwithĀ
commands. Here is an example. In the preferences file the suffix
"@{u}.doc@{uu}" associated with "@{u}more@{uu}". To display the file "foo.doc" just type @{b}show@{ub}
@{b}foo.doc @{ub}and it will be displayed using the program @{b}more@{ub}.

I use the word suffix loosely. The "suffix" does not have to be at the end of
the filename it can occur at the beginning or anywhere in the filename. The
prefix "mod." is associated with mod files even though the filename starts
with "mod."

Commands can be as simple as a program name or as complex as multiple commands.
In the sample preferences supplied with this package, a complex command is
used for the suffix ".1". This command is useful when you have unix man pages
stored in their original Troff format. I have included a simple alternative
for UN*X man command stored in the @{"man" link "man" 0} directory included with this archive.
Click on man for more details.
@endnode



@node "useshow" "Using Show"
@next "showprefs"
@prev "whatis"
Show can be run either from the Workbench by clicking on its icon or by the
CLI

@{b}@{u}CLI Usage:@{ub}@{uu}
 Typing show with no arguments will show the following message:

  @{b}USAGE: show [-f suffix] filename [[-f suffix] filename2...]@{ub}

 The @{u}-f@{uu} parameter forces the filename to be associated with a certain suffix.
Note that @{u}-f@{uu} changes the suffix for the next filename only. To
override the suffix of two or more files, you must specify @{u}-f@{uu} suffix for all
the files. If a suffix is not recognized in the filename or the suffix specified
with @{u}-f@{uu} is invalid the following message will appear:

@{b}ERROR: suffix in <file> not found@{ub}  where <file> is the filename specified
from the command.

 Show also works with wildcards. For example: @{b}show #?.guide@{ub} will invoke a
Multiview (if Multiview is associated with .guide in the preferences program)
for each guide file in the current directory.

@{b}@{u}WB Usage@{ub}@{uu}

 Starting Show from Workbench, works a little bit differently than starting Show from the CLI. First if
the selected files have an .info file, Show looks for the
@{b}SHOWSUFFIX@{ub} tooltype to determine which suffix to look for. If no .info is
found, Show looks for suffixes in the filename.

 Show can be started on its own or by multiselecting Show with other files by
holding the SHIFT key and selecting files.

 Double-clicking Show with no other icons opens an ASL requester. You can choose one
file or many using multiple file selection. Selection continues until CANCEL is hit.
@endnode


@node "showprefs" "Show Preferences Program"
@next "man"
@prev "useshow"
The Show preferences program is used to create the preferences file. The
preferences file is used by show to hold the suffixes and commands associated
with them.

When you enter the Show preferences program the following screen will appear:

 +------------------------------------------------------+--+--+
 +------------------------------------------------------+--+--+
 |	  Show V1.0					      |
 |   ®1994 Jeff Shepherd		     @{"Suffixes" link "Suffixes" 0}        |
 |					   +-------------+-+  |
 |	   @{"Suffix" link "Suffix" 0}                         |             | |  |
 |     +-------------+			   |		 | |  |
 |     +-------------+			   |		 | |  |
 |					   |		 | |  |
 |	  @{"Command" link "Command" 0}                         |             | |  |
 |     +-------------+			   |		 | |  |
 |     +-------------+			   |		 | |  |
 |					   +-------------+-+  |
 |	 @{"Asynchronous" link "asynch" 0}                     +---+ +----+ +---+ |
 |	     +-+			   |@{"New" link "New" 0}||@{"Copy" link "Copy" 0}||@{"Del" link "Delete" 0}||
 |	     +-+			   +---+ +----+ +---+ |
 |   +------+		      +-----+		  +--------+  |
 |   | @{"Save" link "save" 0}|                 | @{"Use" link "Use" 0}|             | @{"Cancel" link "Cancel" 0}|  |
 |   +------+		      +-----+		  +--------+  |
 |							      |
 +------------------------------------------------------------+

Here are the Preferences Menus. They function as close as possible to the ones
used by the Workbench preferences programs.

 @{b}@{u}Project Menu@{ub}@{uu}
 @{"Open" link "open" 0}
 @{"SaveĀAs..." link "saveas" 0}
 @{"About" link "MenuAbout" 0}
 @{"Quit" link "Quit" 0}

 @{b}@{u}Edit Menu@{ub}@{uu}
 @{"LastĀSaved" link "lastsave" 0}
 @{"Restore" link "restore" 0}

@{b}@{u}Note on the preference program@{ub}@{uu}

I have made the preferences program as font-adaptive as possible. The text
used by the preference program is the "System Default Font" of the Font
preferences. If the window cannot be fit into the screen using this font, the
preferences program will default to topaz 8. Also if the font changes while
the preferences program is still running, it will close itself and re-render
itself using the new fonts. Also if the screenmode changes, the preferences
program will reopen itself on the new screen. I don't think any preferences
program can boast these features!!!
@endnode

@node "Suffixes" "Suffixes"
@toc "prefcom"
The Suffixes listview shows a list of the currently defined suffixes. Use the
up and down arrows to reveal more suffixes. To select a suffix just click on
its name, the @{"Suffix" link "Suffix" 0} box, @{"Command" link "Command" 0} box and @{"Asynchronous" link "Asynch" 0} checkbox will show the
suffix, command and Asynchronous flag respectively for the suffix.
@endnode

@node "Suffix" "Suffix"
@toc "prefcom"
Allows you to edit the suffix of the currently suffix. If no suffix is
selected anything you type will be ignored. Make sure you press ENTER after
you are done to allow the new suffix to be registered.
@endnode

@node "Command" "Command"
@toc "prefcom"
Allows you to edit the command of the currently suffix. If no suffix is
selected anything you type will be ignored. Make sure you press ENTER after
you are done to allow the new command to be registered.
@endnode

@node "asynch" "Asynchronous"
@toc "prefcom"
If the Asynchronous checkbox is checked, the command is executed
asynchronously ie the program regains control immediately although the command
may still be executing. The way I implemented asynchronous command execution
is tack a "RUN >NIL:" in front of the command. The drawbacks of doing so is
that any errors that might occur will never be shown. If you type "show
<filename>" and nothing happens, clear the Asynchronous checkbox through the
preferences program and run the command again.
@endnode

@node "New" "New"
@toc "prefcom"
Makes a new node a places it at the front of the suffix list. The suffix
defaults to (New Suffix). To edit the suffix or command, click on the string
edit box and change the string. Make sure you press RETURN when finished.
@endnode

@node "Copy" "Copy"
@toc "prefcom"
Copies the currently selected node and places the new node on top of the
suffix list. If no node was selected, this gadget does nothing. Follow the
instructions for the @{"New" link "new" 0} gadget.This option is good when you have multiple
suffixes using the same command.
@endnode

@node "Delete" "Del"
@toc "prefcom"
Deletes the currently selected node. If no node was selected, this gadget does
nothing. @{b}NOTE@{ub}: You cannot get back what you have deleted from this command.
@endnode

@node "Save" "Save"
@toc "prefcom"
Saves the preferences files in ENV: and ENVARC: and exits the program.
@endnode

@node "Use" "Use"
@toc "prefcom"
Saves the preferences files in ENV: and exits the program. The new preferences
will be erased when the computer is turned off.
@endnode

@node "Cancel" "Cancel"
@toc "prefcom"
Exits the preferences program without saving anything.
@endnode

@node "open" "Open"
@toc "prefcom"
Open a previously saved preferences file. An ASL requester will appear to
allow you to choose a file. The default file is
SYS:prefs/presets/prefs.presets.
@endnode

@node "saveas" "SaveĀAs..."
@toc "prefcom"
Allows you save the preferences file under a different name. An ASL requester
will appear to allow you to save the file. The default name is
SYS:prefs/presets/show.presets.
@endnode

@node "MenuAbout" "About Show Menu"
@toc "prefcom"
Brings up a requester showing the version of Show and little text about
@{"myself" link "about" 0}. Click OK to end the requester.
@endnode

@node "Quit" "Quit Show Preferences"
@toc "prefcom"
Quits the preferences program without saving the preferences file. It is the
same as pressing the CANCEL gadget.
@endnode

@node "lastsave" "Last Saved"
Restores the preferences that were last saved using @{"Save" link "Save" 0}.
@endnode

@node "restore" "Restore Preferences"
@toc "prefcom"
Restores the preferences that were loaded when the preferences program began.
@endnode


